Thailand Stocks: Airports of Thailand, Glow, PTT Aromatics

-- B y   A n u c h i t   N g u y e n
-- 
2011-08-01T06:06:44Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-08-01/bualuang-glow-energy-ptt-aromatics-thailand-equity-preview.html
Shares of the following companies had
unusual moves in Thailand trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses and prices are as of the 12:30 p.m. lunch break in
Bangkok.  The SET Index rose 12.29 points, or 1.1 percent, to
1,145.82, heading for the highest close since July 23, 1996.  Oil companies :  PTT Pcl (PTT)  , Thailand’s biggest energy
company, climbed 1.4 percent to 352 baht.  PTT Exploration &
Production Pcl (PTTEP)  , the nation’s only publicly traded oil
explorer, advanced 1.1 percent to 186 baht.  Crude oil advanced from a two-week low in  New York  after
President Barack Obama said leaders of both parties in the U.S.
House and Senate approved a deal to raise the nation’s debt
ceiling, stoking optimism over the economic recovery in the
world’s biggest crude-consuming nation.  Airports of Thailand Pcl (AOT)  , Thailand’s biggest
airfield operator, dropped 3.2 percent to 45.5 baht, the largest
decline since June 2. The company plans to invest about 164
billion baht ($5.5 billion) to expand Suvarnabhumi international
airport, board chairman Tirapol Noparumpa said. The company
plans to move domestic flights from Don Mueang airport to
Suvarnabhumi airport by 2016, Tirapol said.  Glow Energy Pcl (GLOW)  , the nation’s largest private
power supplier by market value, fell 1.3 percent to 55.75 baht,
the most in two weeks. Profit in the second quarter dropped 25
percent to 886.4 million baht.  PTT Aromatics & Refining Pcl (PTTAR)  , the operator of
the second-biggest refinery, advanced 1.2 percent to 43 baht,
set for the highest close since April 19. The company posted net
income of 2.14 billion baht in the second quarter compared with
a revised net loss of 522.3 million baht a year earlier.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Anuchit Nguyen in Bangkok at 
 anguyen@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Darren Boey at 
 dboey@bloomberg.net . 